}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 History:}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 The {\u8216\'91}Modern Literal Version New Testament{\u8217\'92} came about because of a young Christian{\u8217\'92}s goal to find an accurate \softline
Modern English translation from which to study in 1987. The New American Standard contradicted itself in Matthew \softline
5:17 and Ephesians 2:15 for example. Almost all other Modern English translations do not claim to be literal or word-for-word and most that do are really not. Concordance look-ups showed the non-uniform Greek word renderings in all \softline
existing translations, this too became an  issue of concern.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 A group of Christians, of which this new Christian was a part, were actively doing topical, }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 English and Greek word \softline
studies with their Bibles and {\u8220\'93}Englishman{\u8217\'92}s Greek Concordances.{\u8221\'94} They discovered the ASV was the most accurate \softline
translation. They initially started a study bible cross reference section for it. }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Then an idea grew to do a computerized \softline
revision of the 1901 American Standard Version for the public domain, code named {\u8220\'93}ASV3{\u8221\'94}. These ideas were dropped \softline
with too many problems: the underlining Greek text, massive footnoting, archaic words, inconsistent Greek word \softline
translations, etc. A better idea grew, the creation of a modern (English) literal version (which later became the name). \softline
A group of workers, computer owners and scholars, who believe in the total authority and inspiration of the Bible, \softline
devoted time, advise, software and work for the project. Now, over 27 years later, at least 35 experts in the original \softline
language have contributed work needed to make this translation a reality. Many others, about 170, have also helped with \softline
large amounts of proofreading, English comprehension, double-checking Greek definitions, compounds, synonyms, \softline
Greek concordance look-ups, accuracy checks and/or other menial (but extremely essential) tasks. A few thousand \softline
corrections have been received via E-mail for changes, so far. We will never be able to express our gratitude enough to \softline
all of these people, living & dead.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 The MLV was the first translation to use the power of the computer (8086) and would have been impossible before the \softline
computer age. This translation would have been impossible without Word Perfect (special thanks to Corel Corporation). \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 The original intentions and guidelines for the {\u8216\'91}Modern Literal Version{\u8217\'92} were:}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 1. To translate the original language, word-for-word into English. Then to further boost the accuracy of the MLV, to \softline
translate the same Greek word into as few different English words as possible. We also do this for English words by not \softline
using them for different Greek words. Careful attention was paid to synonyms, antonyms and compound words. One way \softline
to look at this is: if God wanted 10 different words used instead of one single Greek word, the inspired writers would \softline
have penned it that way. The New Testament is its own best commentary when you see the same Greek word translated \softline
into the same English word throughout. We call this {\u8216\'91}uniform and consistent' translating and we believe we're the first \softline
translation to ever attempt this. This form of translation is an extremely hard task, not one that many translators would \softline
ever take the time to do, even now that it is possible with computers. More information is in the {\u8216\'91}Wording Statistics' \softline
section later.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 2. The goal of the MLV was not to make it perfect everyday English, but try to make it understandable to the majority \softline
of English speaking people, while remaining literal. Sentences in the MLV may start with conjunctions like 'and,' 'but,' \softline
'for' and {\u8216\'91}because'. This was so we could split incredible long sentences (50+ words) that were appearing as we translated \softline
into English. The Modern Literal Version is about junior high school reading level.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 3. To translate some verses that have been misinterpreted for years by many religious groups, as close as possible to the \softline
original language.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 4. To use }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 italics }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 for supplied words and use supplied words as opposed to paraphrasing. We want people to see what we \softline
added.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 5. To translate the money and measuring systems of the Bible into some understandable form. (See the Appendix.) \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 6. To use {\u8216\'91}will' for all future tenses. Though it is not proper modern English. It is the way most English people speak. \softline
{\u8216\'91}Shall' is retained in questions.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 7. To use paragraph format. Verse format take meanings out of context.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 8. To use the more proper {\u8216\'91}may' or {\u8216\'91}might' for the subjunctive mood verbs. The ASV used {\u8216\'91}should' and {\u8216\'91}shall.' Shall is \softline
not consider {\u8216\'91}conditional' in modern English, but future tense. (See more in the Appendix II section).\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 9. To arrange the Greek word order into normal English word order of subject verb object, (SVO). Following Greek word \softline
order is not more literal or accurate; if we retained the Greek order it would be more like an interlinear without the Greek.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 10. To footnote or explain in the Appendix places where a literal translation could not be understood or was an idiom \softline
used by the common Greeks. For example: {\u8216\'91}into/to the ages' is an idiom for {\u8216\'91}forever'. (These are not as common as many \softline
people would have you believe).\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 11. To render active tense verbs as {\u8216\'91}is/are verb-ing' to help show action. Many people wrongly say the {\u8216\'91}-eth' ending used \softline
in older translations meant continual action. It was simply the way they spoke before the 1800's.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 12. To fix the preposition and conjunction problems that plague all translations. Our biggest fix is the English word {\u8216\'91}for' \softline
that was used even in the ASV for several Greek words which mean {\u8216\'91}because of,' {\u8216\'91}because,' {\u8216\'91}to,' {\u8216\'91} toward,' {\u8216\'91}of,' {\u8216\'91}in/on \softline
behalf of' and a mild form of {\u8216\'91}because.' The MLV translated all Greek words that mean {\u8216\'91}because,' {\u8216\'91}because of' and {\u8216\'91}in/on \softline
behalf of' as such. The other meanings are shown by use of asterisks (*) with the two most common Greek words \softline
translated as {\u8216\'91}for' ({\u8216\'91}eis', G1520 = *for and G1063 {\u8216\'91}gar' = for*).\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 13. }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 To avoid inconsistencies caused by splitting up the translators and proofreaders into groups . A typical translation \softline
may have 100 plus people but by the time you split them into 25 or more committees the number of people in one \softline
particular book might be as little as 4 and those different groups can cause stylistic and translation variations. Those who \softline
volunteer with the MLV tend to work all the way through the New Testament, so in the MLV the total per book far \softline
exceeds any committee type translation.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 14. To include a Harmony of the New Testament with AD dates, which gives a person the ability to read the Bible the \softline
way is was written or in chronological order. (Start at Mark, then go to Acts.)\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 The 1987-1999 version, roughly 95% completed, was formally U.S. copyrighted and placed into the {\u8216\'91}Christian Library{\u8217\'92} \softline
in June, 1999 at http://www.ChristianLibrary.org because of needed bandwidth and limited funds \softline
http://www.ModernLiteralVersion.org was added in 2014.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 A challenge to all who think that another translation is more accurate to the original Greek than the MLV. Show us the \softline
correction needed! Please remember {\u8216\'91}thus saith the Greek{\u8217\'92} not 'my version says.' This translation needs to be judged by \softline
the Greek, not anything else!\par
