{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 [APPENDIX I]}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 The primary goal is to keep the MLV free from theological concerns and traditions by translating as literally as possible \softline
while retaining modern language and readability. The {\u8216\'91}Open Translation{\u8217\'92} approach is also a great {\u8216\'91}checks & balance{\u8217\'92} \softline
system.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 The Greeks wrote in present tense to give the reader the feeling of {\u8216\'91}being there{\u8217\'92} and so this translation leaves present \softline
tense unchanged.}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Asterisks (*) are used for footnoting of words listed here in the Appendix.}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  These are for the few instances where the \softline
English translation does not lend itself to a satisfactory meaning of the underlying Greek word. In addition to this, we \softline
also use an asterisk to denote the difference between one English word that is being used for two different Greek words \softline
(see }{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Age*}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  below.) This also aids word studies substantially.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 A hyphen (-) is used in those places where two English words come from one Greek word. It is of particular benefit to \softline
Greek scholars and the student who wishes, (when they are published), to cross-reference words to the MLV \softline
Concordance & Greek Lexicon.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 Italicized words }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 are words not found directly in the Greek but are implied by the context. These words are sometimes \softline
needed to help show action, tense and to expand the meaning of some words that the English does not capture. Since the \softline
MLV is literal and not {\u8216\'91}thought-for-thought{\u8217\'92}, supplied words help greatly for those phrases which are exceptionally \softline
difficult to read. By signifying these words through italics the reader has the option to disregard them if they wish to do \softline
so. The articles {\u8216\'91}a{\u8217\'92} and {\u8216\'91}an{\u8217\'92} are not found in the Greek and so are always supplied though never marked.}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Paragraphs are used in this translation with no credence given to chapter or verse numbers since verse formats, chapter \softline
titles or other special formatting often takes ideas out of context, (see Mark 8:34 to 9:1 for an example of this). Double \softline
spaced paragraphs was an attempt to arrange by subject. Single spaced paragraphs are for conversations or for sub-topics. \softline
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 We did not include subject headings as we felt this would only reflect our opinions and we do not want this in the Word \softline
of God.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Single or double quotation marks are not used in this translation because they are not found in the original language and \softline
adding them would be an area of opinion. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \cf3\fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 We also do not capitalize pronouns that appear to be referring to God ({\u8216\'91}Him,{\u8217\'92} {\u8216\'91}He{\u8217\'92} etc). This is again to avoid having \softline
our opinion in the translation as the Greek does not make these distinctions.}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \cf3\fs20 Red Lettering}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  or }{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Bold Lettering}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  (electronic or printed edition) is used for the words of Jesus, God the Father and the \softline
Holy Spirit even in an indirect quote as in Acts 26. If you do not believe the }{\plain \fs20 \cf3\fs20 RED}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  or }{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 BOLD}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  should be used in a certain \softline
area, please ignore.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Greek is participle crazy. A rather large number of participles are found in Greek sentences and it is common that a \softline
sentence contains no main verb but just participle after participle. We have added in supplied words in an effort to stay \softline
more literal and yet break these into smaller more readable English sentences..\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
