}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 (MLV Dictionary in e-Sword)}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Age* }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 is Strong{\u8217\'92}s Dictionary number 165 (onward, we will abbreviate as G165 for electronic & book uniformity). It is \softline
very much the way we think of a person{\u8217\'92}s {\u8216\'91}age{\u8217\'92}. The other {\u8216\'91}age, ages{\u8217\'92} not marked is a period of time. This {\u8216\'91}age{\u8217\'92} is also \softline
translated as {\u8216\'91}world{\u8217\'92} context determines which word. See }{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 World}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  below.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Admonish }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 means to {\u8216\'91}instruct with warning{\u8217\'92} G3560.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Ambassador*}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  see Apostle below.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 And }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 from G2532 was used like we use a comma in lists.  We have kept these {\u8220\'93}and{\u8221\'94} and any other Greek words that we \softline
could even if not {\u8216\'91}English teacher approved.{\u8217\'92}\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Apostle }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 is a transliterated word. The English equivalent would be {\u8216\'91}one sent{\u8217\'92} with the meaning of {\u8216\'91}one sent on a mission.{\u8217\'92} \softline
Apostle has been kept when speaking of Jesus{\u8217\'92} apostles. Ambassador* is the other rendering of this Greek word, G652.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Appointed*}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  is G5087 which literally is {\u8216\'91}placed{\u8217\'92} but we just don{\u8217\'92}t speak that way in English. The other {\u8216\'91}appointed{\u8217\'92} \softline
without the * is from compounds of G5021 which is {\u8216\'91}command or appoint.{\u8217\'92}\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Assuredly}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  is literally {\u8216\'91}amen{\u8217\'92} which roughly means {\u8216\'91}so be it.{\u8217\'92} Jesus said this, (sometimes twice), at the beginning of His \softline
teachings. In the KJV this was translated {\u8216\'91}verily, verily{\u8217\'92}. G281.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Baptism }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 see Immersion.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Be, is, was, were, being, been}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  verbs are generally {\u8216\'91}helper words{\u8217\'92} added to other English verbs, adjectives or rarely \softline
nouns to translate some Greek verbs. When they are not {\u8216\'91}helper words{\u8217\'92} then they are from compounds of G1096 \softline
({\u8216\'91}become{\u8217\'92}), G1510 ({\u8216\'91}be, is, was...{\u8217\'92}) and sometimes but rarely G2192 ({\u8216\'91}have, hold, help{\u8217\'92}) and G5225 (denoted as be*, \softline
is*, was*, being*; exist, possess).}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Believe, belief, faith, faithful, trust}{\plain \fs20 \fs20   in verb, adjective, adverb or noun forms are some of those very few Greek words \softline
(G4100, G4102, G4103) which carry more meaning than the English equivalent. These words also}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  carry the meaning: \softline
{\u8216\'91}obey{\u8217\'92}, {\u8216\'91}had been persuaded.{\u8217\'92} The antonym of {\u8216\'91}believe{\u8217\'92} is {\u8216\'91}disobey{\u8217\'92} in the Greek language (G544). See John 3:36 for \softline
both words together.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Believe on}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  literally in the majority of all places in the New Testament means {\u8216\'91}believe upon.{\u8217\'92}\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Believe in}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  literally in the majority of all places in the New Testament means {\u8216\'91}believe into{\u8217\'92}. Similar expression to Mat 
28:19 {\u8216\'91}... into the name... {\u8216\'91}.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Belt}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  is impossible to tell from context if it is a simple belt or a complex series of leather straps used to hold tools, \softline
weapons, money or a belt of armor. The girdle (belt) was worn across the waist or across the chest. G2223.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Between* }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 is an idiom for {\u8216\'91}up }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 through}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  the middle,{\u8217\'92} G3319.}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Bowels}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  are where the Greeks thought the emotions were born. This is where we get expressions such as {\u8216\'91}desires of the \softline
heart,{\u8217\'92} {\u8216\'91}gut feeling,{\u8217\'92} {\u8216\'91}nervous stomach{\u8217\'92} and so on. G4698.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Brethren}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  is specifically {\u8216\'91}brothers{\u8217\'92} but used more often to describe kinfolk, whether by family ties or by the blood of \softline
Jesus. Though translated from a Greek masculine noun, G80, the word includes males and females in context.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Centurions }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 were military commanders of over 100 soldiers. They were highly esteemed individuals of society. (G2763, \softline
Latin root; G1543, Greek.)\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Charity}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  in the MLV does not mean {\u8216\'91}money.{\u8217\'92} It may include money but literally means {\u8216\'91}good, merciful or kind acts.{\u8217\'92} \softline
G1654\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Christ }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 is a transliterated Greek adjective, G5547, that would translate as {\u8216\'91}anointed.{\u8217\'92} Messiah is the Hebrew translation. \softline
In the 2015 version it was rendered as {\u8216\'91}Jesus the Christ{\u8217\'92} either a title or a description depending on your view. \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Church}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 , see }{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Congregation* }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 below.}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20  \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Class}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  (a noun) is the priestly service limited to a stated series of days. G2183.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Coming}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  (as in Second Coming), G3952, has been translated more properly as {\u8216\'91}}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 presence.{\u8217\'92}\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Commanders}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  were military commanders of over 1000 soldiers. G5506\par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Congregation* }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 was the original translation by Tyndale in the first English translation from the Greek and then later \softline
changed to 'church' by the Reformed Protestants in the Geneva Bible, a man-made word. Then perpetuated by the \softline
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Catholic Church and Church of England until today (now because of tradition). These man-made tradition has been used \softline
over the centuries to promote a 'church' not the 'congregation' of our Lord Jesus. The word could be translated 'assembly' \softline
which Robert Young did in his translation and also the MLV at one time. In Modern English most think of "church" as \softline
a building. The original Greek word, even in the Bible, carries no special reverence. }{\plain \fs20 \fs20  It is used to describe Jews, a mob, \softline
a local congregation, and the congregation of faithful, obedience believers worldwide as in Matthew 16:18, Act 2:47, \softline
called the one body in Eph. 4:1-6, Eph 5:23 and others. Translating this Greek word as {\u8216\'91}the called out{\u8217\'92} would be like \softline
saying a {\u8216\'91}pineapple{\u8217\'92} is an {\u8216\'91}apple produced by a pine tree.{\u8217\'92} The word was in use in all Greek writings which meant some \softline
form of {\u8216\'91}leaving your home to assemble elsewhere, generally in public for town announcements.{\u8217\'92}}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  (G1577; once from \softline
its synonym G4864}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 ).}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Cohort }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 is a Roman military term to describe a group of 600 soldiers. G4686.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}\pard \fs20
{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Consequently}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  though an adverb in English is used for a Greek particle, G686 & G687, consequently is not exactly \softline
{\u8216\'91}therefore{\u8217\'92} in English. It means that the previous statement is probably so or will become so.}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 \tab \tab \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Container(s).}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  The bible uses Hebrew and Greek measurements like {\u8216\'91}cor{\u8217\'92} which is a measurement of volume, about \softline
90 gallons. We rendered these words as volume + the word {\u8216\'91}container{\u8217\'92} like {\u8216\'91}ninety-gallon container{\u8217\'92} vs. footnoting \softline
everyone of them; see Luke 16:7.\par
