}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 The}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  occurs in Greek same as in English with one major exception, {\u8216\'91}the{\u8217\'92} is used with proper nouns. {\u8216\'91}Paul{\u8217\'92} is {\u8216\'91}the \softline
Paul.{\u8217\'92} We have tried to include all definite articles other than those with proper nouns. Many would say they should \softline
be dropped in some places but our opinion in this matter is if the inspired writers included {\u8216\'91}the{\u8217\'92} then we should put it \softline
there in English whenever possible. The inspired writers could have left {\u8216\'91}the{\u8217\'92} out in most of these questionable \softline
places and it still would have been good Greek grammar, especially in Paul{\u8217\'92}s & Luke{\u8217\'92}s writings who were fluent \softline
speaking Greeks. G3588.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Unimpeachable}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  is from a Greek word, G423, that really does not go well into English. The word is only used in the \softline
qualifications of elders/overseers/pastors/shepherds in the Bible. It means someone who is not under an accusation of \softline
any kind (that is, blameless and guiltless) and has a impeccable reputation. This and {\u8216\'91}believing children{\u8217\'92} are the only \softline
two qualifications that are not learned or cannot be learned by a person who reaches to be an \softline
elder/overseer/pastor/shepherd.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 View}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  is a stronger {\u8216\'91}see{\u8217\'92} or {\u8216\'91}look.{\u8217\'92} Means to {\u8216\'91}view as a spectator{\u8217\'92} or like our expression {\u8216\'91}view from the side lines.{\u8217\'92} \softline
View is to pay more attention to what you see or look at. You can substitute {\u8216\'91}see{\u8217\'92} if it is truly awkward some verse. \softline
G2334.\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Washings}{\plain \fs20 \super\fs20 *}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  or immersions. See }{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Immerse}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 .\par
}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 Wormwood}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  may be a person or thing and an actual substance which is bitter tasting. The reader will have to decide \softline
what they believe it is in context. G894.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 You}{\plain \fs20 \b\super\fs20 *}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 ,}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20  your}{\plain \fs20 \b\super\fs20 *}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 , }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 is plural {\u8216\'91}you{\u8217\'92} and {\u8216\'91}your{\u8217\'92}. By keeping these you will find teachings in the MLV that is lost in almost all \softline
other modern English translations.}{\plain \fs20 \fs20   We have never understood why modern translators would lose plural {\u8216\'91}you.{\u8217\'92}\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
