{\plain \fs28 \b\fs28 Read the New Testament in Better Ways}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 For better understanding, read the New Testament }{\plain \fs28 \fs28 the way it should have been \softline
arranged and is closer to chronological order:\par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 Mark, Matthew, John, Luke,\par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 Acts: The Book of Conversions\par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 James, 1&2 Thessalonians, Galatians,}{\plain \fs28 \fs28  1&2 Corinthians, Romans,\par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 Ephesians, Philippians, Colossians,}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 1&2 Peter, Jude,}{\plain \fs28 \fs28  Philemon,}{\plain \fs28 \fs28  1 Timothy, Titus, Hebrews, 2 Timothy,\par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 1-3 John, Revelation.\par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 (A }{\plain \fs28 \fs28 {\u8220\'93}Simple Reading Schedule{\u8221\'94}}{\plain \fs28 \fs28  is in Appendix II for a 2 month through the MLV.)\par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 To read the New Testament in chronological order, go to Mark chapter 1 and start \softline
reading then to Acts 1.}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \fs28 You should read the MLV once all the way through and do not use any other \softline
translation during this time. The MLV{\u8217\'92}s strongest feature is its uniformity of \softline
English wording & underlying Greek wording, by using another translation during \softline
this time you will not be able to learn from this uniformity as would a native \softline
Greek.}{\plain \fs24 \par
