\pard \fs20\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883
{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 merely entertained as a thought. It may be a statement viewed emotionally, as desired, doubted, or wished.}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 {\u8217\'92} \softline
(Roberts Grammar, pg. 130.) Subjunctive mood verbs have always been a problem in translations in the past \softline
600 years and have plagued the MLV as well. These verbs are denoted by the words {\u8216\'91}should, may or might{\u8217\'92} and \softline
are added in front of them. These subjunctive mood verbs in Greek are most often preceded by a {\u8216\'91}conditional \softline
particle{\u8217\'92} or some other part of speech (see G302, G1437, G1437a, G1875, G2579, G3752). These conditional \softline
statements, when translated into English, begin with words like {\u8216\'91}if, whoever, whatever, whenever{\u8217\'92} and the \softline
{\u8216\'91}should, may or might{\u8217\'92} is usually dropped, (too wordy and confusing for modern English). Some of these \softline
conditional statements are denoted at the beginning with {\u8216\'91}*that{\u8217\'92} (G3705), {\u8216\'91}that*{\u8217\'92} or {\u8216\'91}in order that{\u8217\'92}(G2443). We \softline
have translated all of these in places like Mark 4:27 for the sake of remaining as literal as possible even though \softline
modern English would abbreviate the sentence down to only the first {\u8216\'91}should{\u8217\'92}.\par
}\pard \fs20\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}\pard \fs20\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 In Greek translation, places where subjunctive mood verbs occur with G3661 are generally changed to \softline
imperative mood (this determined by context). An example of this is the ending of Mark 5:7 where the demon is \softline
speaking to Jesus and says: {\u8216\'91}Do not torment me{\u8217\'92} where subjunctive mood would be meaningless: {\u8216\'91}You may not \softline
torment me.{\u8217\'92} Even though a conditional statement does carry a future tense feeling, the improper use of {\u8216\'91}shall{\u8217\'92} \softline
and {\u8216\'91}will{\u8217\'92} was dropped. ({\u8216\'91}Shall{\u8217\'92} is Old English present tense of {\u8216\'91}should{\u8217\'92} as well as first person future tense; a \softline
current 13 year old has no idea about {\u8216\'91}shall{\u8217\'92} meaning {\u8216\'91}should.{\u8217\'92}) Even though, {\u8216\'91}may never{\u8217\'92} and {\u8216\'91}should we \softline
give?{\u8217\'92} might sound better as {\u8216\'91}will never{\u8217\'92} or {\u8216\'91}shall we give?{\u8217\'92} we opted to keep subjunctive mood as such as \softline
opposed to making them future tense. {\u8216\'91}Will{\u8217\'92} in modern language, even though {\u8216\'91}it has not happened,{\u8217\'92} is \softline
frequently thought of as}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  {\u8216\'91}is absolutely going to take place,{\u8217\'92} which would be incorrect in most places. The \softline
inspired writers could have use future tense if that was what they meant.}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}\pard \fs20\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}\pard \fs20\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883
{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 TRADITIONS AND SELLING BIBLES}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  \par
}\pard \fs20\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 We are not here to serve the god of Money. }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 We have removed many traditional or transliterated words by \softline
translating them unless they are {\u8216\'91}thus saith the Greek{\u8217\'92} such }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 words as: angel, baptism, baptize, baptist, blessed, \softline
church, doctrine, gospel, saint, and satan.}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  We have not followed traditional translations unless they too are {\u8216\'91}thus \softline
saith the Greek.{\u8217\'92} We will}{\plain \fs20 \b\i\fs20  not}{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20  }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 be putting them back in for Money{\u8217\'92}s sake.  People need to learn about what God \softline
really said and pitch out tradition.\par
}\pard \fs20\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 \par
}\pard \fs20\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883
{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 TALKING TO OTHERS ABOUT THE MLV\par
}\pard \fs20\qj\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883 
{\plain \fs20 \b\fs20 \par
}\pard \fs20\qj\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883 
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 One of the best ways to describe the "Modern Literal Version" New Testament translation is that it is the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 first}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  to \softline
adopt many significant translation principles:\line \line 1. It was the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 first}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  translation to use the power of modern computers. All the way back in 1987.\line 2. The MLV was the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 first}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  to attempt to keep Greek uniformity. (Same Greek word translation into the same English \softline
word(s) whenever possible.)\line 3. The MLV was the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 first}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  and }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 only}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  to attempt to keep English uniformity. In other words keeping one specific \softline
English word to represent only one specific Greek word or one of its meanings. (The worst example probably is \softline
the word {\u8216\'91}}{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 will}{\plain \fs20 \fs20 {\u8217\'92} which is the translation of 69 different Greek words in the KJV.)\line 4. The }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 first}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  translation that has no contradictions. This is why the MLV was started in the first place because of the \softline
Mt 5:17 (abolish) vs. Eph 2:15 (abolish) one found in most modern translations; same English word used for 2 \softline
different Greek words. Jesus came to not tear down the old law but to fulfil it, and then abolished it with his dead \softline
on the cross and the 'New Covenant.'\line }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 5. The MLV was the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 first}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  bible translation to be open on the internet for anyone to submit corrections, updates or \softline
help, since 1998 and the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 only }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 published translation to stay open with yearly and web updates.\line 6. The MLV is the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 first}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  to be done by a group of people not divided among committees which instantly creates \softline
inconsistent translations. This means some books in the MLV may have had 40 or more people look over them for \softline
Greek or English problems. No other translation has had this kind of manpower devoted to it!\par
}\pard \fs20\qj\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883 
{\plain \fs20 \fs20 7. The MLV is the }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 first }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 and }{\plain \fs20 \i\fs20 only}{\plain \fs20 \fs20  translation to ever deal with the word {\u8216\'91}for{\u8217\'92}, by translating all the {\u8216\'91}for{\u8217\'92} conjunctions \softline
as {\u8216\'91}because.{\u8217\'92}\par
}\pard \fs20\qj\tx-2188\tx-1055\tx79\tx1213\tx2347\tx3481\tx4615\tx5749\tx6883 
